[
    {
        "content": "<p>Given a single-sorted algebraic theory (aka a Lawvere theory) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>, there seems to be a multisorted algebraic theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T^+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> whose category of algebras/models is the slice category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}/T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span></span></span></span> is the category of single-sorted algebraic theories. Has anybody worked on this? <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> perhaps?</p>\n<p>Something similar holds for categories of suitably \"sorted\" essentially algebraic theories (where such a category is the category of finitary monads on a presheaf category).</p>\n<p>I'm asking because I'm interested in finding a general notion of \"opetope\" that should include something like this, in particular opetopes that arise from invertible unary operations (I could try to draw the picture in my head of what such an opetope might look like if someone wants me to).</p>",
        "id": 263243193,
        "sender_full_name": "Chaitanya Leena Subramaniam",
        "timestamp": 1638332920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know anyone who has studied this.</p>",
        "id": 263280491,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638360943
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I haven't been paying careful attention to everything people are doing with opetopes these days!</p>\n<p>I'm completely convinced of your claim in the case where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> is the terminal Lawvere theory: that is, there's a multisorted algebraic theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1^+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> whose category of algebras is the category of Lawvere theories.</p>",
        "id": 263280857,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361196
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In this paper we proved something similar:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>John Baez, Brandon Coya and Franciscus Rebro, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.08321\">Props in network theory</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 263281019,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361288
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Namely, we showed there's a multisorted algebraic theory whose category of algebras is the category of props.</p>",
        "id": 263281073,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361323
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A prop is a strict symmetric monoidal category whose set of objects is the natural numbers, with the tensor product being addition.   So, a Lawvere theory is the same as a prop where the monoidal product is cartesian.</p>",
        "id": 263281223,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361414
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We proved this theorem because we wanted to reason with props the way people reason with groups or rings: defining them using generators and relations, taking quotients of them by adding extra relations, etc.</p>",
        "id": 263281390,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361500
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we noted that there's also a multisorted algebraic theory whose algebras are Lawvere theories, but if so it was an offhand comment in an appendix, not something we needed.</p>",
        "id": 263281489,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361557
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed for any set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> of sorts, there's a multisorted Lawvere theory whose algebras are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-sorted Lawvere theories.  You will want to reason at this level of generality if you want to iterate the slice construction and think about \"cartesian opetopes\".</p>",
        "id": 263281586,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638361594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is true, though I haven't seen it explicitly studied somewhere. For a proof, recall that the categories of models for multisorted algebraic theories are precisely the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/locally%20strongly%20finitely%20presentable\">[[locally strongly finitely presentable]]</a> (LSFP) categories. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span></span></span></span> is LSFP, as mentioned by John. Furthermore, the slice of a LSFP category is LSFP (see, for instance, Remark 3 of Centazzo–Rosický–Vitale's <a href=\"http://www.math.muni.cz/~rosicky/papers/char.pdf\">A characterization of locally <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">D</span></span></span></span>-presentable categories</a>, taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">D</span></span></span></span> to be the class of finite discrete categories). Therefore, for any algebraic theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>, the slice category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}/T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> is LSFP and hence the category of models for some multisorted algebraic theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T^+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. The same is true for essentially algebraic theories for the same reason (here taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">D</span></span></span></span> to be the class of finite categories). However, I suspect that it would be difficult to find a syntactic characterisation of the algebraic theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T^+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> in question (conversely, coslices of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span></span></span></span> are relatively straightforward to describe syntactically, but more difficult to characterise categorically).</p>",
        "id": 263291201,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1638366118
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Doesn't the case of general <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> follow formally from the case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, using the fact that a slice of a monadic functor is monadic?</p>",
        "id": 263293768,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1638367172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To spell it out a little more explicitly, you're saying that, since <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U : \\mathrm{AlgTh} \\to \\mathrm{Set}^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9146em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9146em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is monadic (for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>), that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mi>X</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>U</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}/T \\to (\\mathrm{Set}^X)/UT</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1646em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9146em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> is monadic (and the latter is again a power of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, exhibiting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{AlgTh}/T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">AlgTh</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> as the category of models for a multisorted algebraic theory). Is that right? That also seems like a nice argument – I hadn't considered that the slice adjunction preserves monadicity.</p>",
        "id": 263304796,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1638371507
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we need something like \"the slice of a finitary monadic functor is finitary monadic\", since it's <em>finitary</em> monads that correspond to Lawvere theories.   </p>\n<p>I don't know such a result, but it's probably true....</p>",
        "id": 263311691,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1638374223
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Baez-Dolan.20slice.20of.20an.20algebraic.20theory/near/263304796\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>That also seems like a nice argument – I hadn't considered that the slice adjunction preserves monadicity.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>To give credit where it's due, this argument was suggested by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276995\">@Chaitanya Leena Subramaniam</span> in an email; I just observed that the slice adjunction does in fact preserve monadicity.</p>",
        "id": 263323675,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1638378695
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Baez-Dolan.20slice.20of.20an.20algebraic.20theory/near/263311691\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think we need something like \"the slice of a finitary monadic functor is finitary monadic\", since it's <em>finitary</em> monads that correspond to Lawvere theories.   </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I think so.  A forgetful functor is \"finitary monadic\" iff it is monadic and finitely accessible (since left adjoints are always cocontinuous), and the slice of a finitely accessible functor is finitely accessible (since colimits in slice categories are created in the base).</p>",
        "id": 263324039,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1638378845
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks everyone! The case of the terminal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-sorted Lawvere theory is in Bénabou's <em>Structures algébriques dans les catégories</em> (cf. paragraph III of the Introduction and Section 3.2). As <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> mentioned, the general case follows since slicing preserves monadicity and finitariness. </p>\n<p>I'm actually interested in a dependently sorted version of this, where a dependently sorted algebraic theory is a finitary monad on presheaves on what Makkai calls a \"simple one-way\" category. Since the category of elements of a presheaf on a simple category is once again a simple category, the same argument shows that the Baez-Dolan slice construction exists for dependently sorted algebraic theories.</p>",
        "id": 263346288,
        "sender_full_name": "Chaitanya Leena Subramaniam",
        "timestamp": 1638387567
    }
